# 🌐 Computer Networking Fundamentals

Notes on how data moves across the internet, mapped directly to my hands-on builds.

## The OSI Model Breakdown

| Layer | Name | Protocol Used in My Server | Responsibility |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Layer 7** | Application | **HTTP** | Parses the raw text format (`HTTP/1.1 200 OK`) so the browser can render HTML. |
| **Layer 4** | Transport | **TCP** | Manages the reliable connection stream (`socket.SOCK_STREAM`) and handshakes between ports. |
| **Layer 3** | Network | **IP** | Routes the packets to the right destination address (`127.0.0.1`). |

## Key Takeaways from Mini-Server Build
* **Sockets** are an abstraction layer provided by the Operating System that lets our code tap directly into Layer 4 (Transport).
* Without an application-level standard like **HTTP/1.1**, data sent over a raw TCP socket would just be meaningless binary garbage to a browser.
